  "prompt": "How do you cook cube steak?",
  "response": "Cube steak can be a delicious and affordable meal when cooked properly. Here's a breakdown of how to cook it, with a few different methods to choose from:\n\n**Key to Success:**  Cube steak can be tough if overcooked.  The goal is to cook it quickly and avoid drying it out.\n\n**General Preparation Steps (Applies to All Methods):**\n\n1.  **Tenderizing (Optional, but Recommended):**\n    *   Cube steak has already been mechanically tenderized, but you can do a little more to ensure tenderness.\n    *   **Methods:**\n        *   **Pounding:** Lightly pound the steak again with a meat mallet, just a few gentle taps on each side.  Don't flatten it too much.\n        *   **Marinating:** Marinate for at least 30 minutes (longer is fine, even overnight in the refrigerator).  Good marinade options include:\n            *   Soy sauce, Worcestershire sauce, lemon juice, garlic, and a touch of sugar.\n            *   Buttermilk or yogurt with spices.\n            *   A simple vinaigrette.\n\n2.  **Seasoning:**  Generously season the steak on both sides with salt, pepper, and any other spices you like.  Garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, and dried herbs (like thyme or rosemary) are all great choices.\n\n3.  **Dredging (Optional, but Common):**  Dredging the steak in flour (or a mix of flour and cornmeal) before cooking helps create a crispy crust.\n    *   **How to Dredge:** Place the seasoned steak in a shallow dish containing flour (or flour mixture). Press the steak into the flour to coat it evenly on both sides. Shake off any excess flour.\n\n**Cooking Methods:**\n\n**1. Pan-Frying (Most Common):**\n\n*   **What You'll Need:** Heavy skillet (cast iron is excellent), oil (vegetable, canola, or peanut), tongs or spatula.\n\n*   **Instructions:**\n    1.  Heat a thin layer of oil in the skillet over medium-high heat until shimmering.  The oil should be hot but not smoking.\n    2.  Carefully place the dredged (or undredged) steak in the hot oil, leaving space between the steaks if possible (cook in batches if necessary).\n    3.  Cook for 2-3 minutes per side, or until golden brown and cooked through.  *Do not overcook.*  The internal temperature should reach 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C) for medium.\n    4.  Remove the steak from the skillet and place it on a plate lined with paper towels to drain.\n    5.  **Optional: Make a Gravy:** After removing the steak, you can make a simple pan gravy in the skillet using the drippings and any remaining flour from the dredging process.  Add beef broth or milk, bring to a simmer, and whisk until thickened. Season with salt, pepper, and herbs.\n\n**2. Braising (For Ultimate Tenderness):**\n\n*   **What You'll Need:** Dutch oven or heavy-bottomed pot, oil, vegetables (onion, carrots, celery), beef broth or stock, herbs (bay leaf, thyme).\n\n*   **Instructions:**\n    1.  Dredge the cube steak in flour (seasoned with salt, pepper, etc.).\n    2.  Heat a little oil in the Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Brown the cube steak on both sides, then remove it from the pot and set aside.\n    3.  Add chopped onion, carrots, and celery to the pot and saut\u00e9 until softened (about 5-7 minutes).\n    4.  Add beef broth or stock (enough to almost cover the steak), along with any herbs (like a bay leaf and thyme sprigs). Bring to a simmer.\n    5.  Return the cube steak to the pot.\n    6.  Cover the pot and reduce the heat to low. Simmer for 1-1.5 hours, or until the steak is very tender.  Check periodically and add more liquid if needed.\n    7.  Remove the steak from the pot and thicken the sauce if desired by simmering it on the stovetop until it reduces.\n\n**3.  Oven-Fried (Healthier Pan-Fried Option):**\n\n*   **What You'll Need:** Baking sheet, wire rack (optional), cooking spray.\n\n*   **Instructions:**\n    1.  Preheat oven to 400\u00b0F (200\u00b0C).\n    2.  Dredge the cube steak in seasoned flour (as described above).\n    3.  Place a wire rack on a baking sheet (this helps the steak crisp up).  Spray the rack with cooking spray.  If you don't have a rack, lightly grease the baking sheet.\n    4.  Place the dredged steak on the rack or baking sheet. Spray the tops of the steak with cooking spray.\n    5.  Bake for 10-15 minutes, flipping halfway through, or until golden brown and cooked through.  Again, don't overcook.\n\n**4.  Grilling (Not Recommended for Beginners):**\n\n*   **What You'll Need:** Grill, oil or cooking spray.\n*   **Instructions:**\n    1.  Preheat grill to medium-high heat.  Clean and lightly oil the grates.\n    2.  Lightly oil cube steaks.\n    3.  Grill cube steak for 1-2 minutes per side.  Cube steak is thin and will cook very quickly.  Keep a close eye on the steak.\n    4.  Grilling is generally not recommended for beginners because the steak can very easily become overcooked.\n\n**Serving Suggestions:**\n\n*   **Classic:** Served with mashed potatoes and gravy.\n*   **Country Fried Steak:**  Served with cream gravy.\n*   **Quick Meal:**  Serve in sandwiches with your favorite toppings.\n*   **Braised:** Served with mashed potatoes, rice or noodles to soak up the braising sauce.\n\n**Important Tips:**\n\n*   **Don't Overcook:** The biggest mistake is overcooking cube steak.  Err on the side of slightly undercooked, as it will continue to cook slightly after you remove it from the heat.\n*   **Hot Pan/Oil:** Make sure your pan and oil are hot before adding the steak to ensure a good sear.\n*   **Don't Crowd the Pan:** Cook the steak in batches if necessary to avoid overcrowding the pan, which can lower the temperature and cause the steak to steam instead of sear.\n*   **Rest the Meat:**  Let the cooked steak rest for a few minutes before serving. This allows the juices to redistribute, resulting in a more tender and flavorful result.\n\nEnjoy your cube steak!  Experiment with different seasonings and sauces to find your favorite way to prepare it.\n",
